    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "Hi!\r\n\r\n>  I deliberately included a invalid BLS signature\r\n\r\n> So does it mean the 32ETH was not transferred successfully to ETH2?\r\n\r\nThe Eth1 deposit contract doesn't check the BLS signature. When your deposit was being processed in Eth2, the Eth2 clients checked the signature and determined it was invalid.\r\n\r\n> Does this mean I forever lost this 32ETH? Is there any way to retrieve them on ETH1?\r\n\r\nUnfortunately, it won't be back. :'(\r\n\r\n> Or maybe I can retrieve them once the transfer function launches on ETH2?\r\n\r\nIt's not about the transfer functionality. It can only be unlocked with a special hard fork.\r\n\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nThat said, when we have BLS12-381 implementation in Eth1, we can have a new deposit contract with on-chain BLS signature verification to protect people from losing ETH with bad deposit signature in the future.",
